Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome back to our 32nd Weekly Dose of Optimism. This was=
 one of those weeks where, come Thursday morning, I had no idea what I was =
going to write about. But, if you look harder enough, in the right places, =
it turns out there=E2=80=99s tons of optimistic stuff happening all around =
us.=20
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
The Weekly Dose is brought to you by=E2=80=A6Sprig [ https://substack.com/r=
edirect/f51d4cfc-2758-49be-99ee-b801dc0c57c0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7=
GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Sprig [ https://substack.com/redirect/f51d4cfc-2758-49be-99ee-b801dc0c57c0?=
j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] lets y=
ou go beyond analytics and improve your product experience with user insigh=
ts, delivered fast. The world=E2=80=99s best product teams, including those=
 at Notion, Loom, and Robinhood, use Sprig=E2=80=99s in-product surveys and=
 prototype tests to capture insights rich from their users and build better=
 products.
Sprig [ https://substack.com/redirect/f51d4cfc-2758-49be-99ee-b801dc0c57c0?=
j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] is pow=
erful on its own, but you can unlock its real power when you integrate Spri=
g with the rest of your tech stack to effortlessly turn insights into actio=
ns. That=E2=80=99s why Sprig is excited to announce a new one-click integra=
tion with Amplitude. This highly-requested integration helps product manage=
rs pair Amplitude=E2=80=99s product analytics with Sprig=E2=80=99s qualitat=
ive user feedback to understand the =E2=80=9Cwhy=E2=80=9D behind users=E2=
=80=99 actions. Imagine launching an A/B test and actually knowing why one =
version outperformed the other. Or noticing a drop-off and being able to pr=
ecisely identify the cause of it.
Here=E2=80=99s what you can do with the Sprig and Amplitude [ https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/f51d4cfc-2758-49be-99ee-b801dc0c57c0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qif=
Q.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] integration:
Continuously track your critical user journeys to surface pain points and u=
nderstand how to solve them.=C2=A0
Detect trends in your conversion or onboarding flow and pinpoint the exact =
reasons driving them.
Collect user feedback and analyze the results by segment or create your own=
 cohorts.
(1) Eli Lilly to Cut Price of Insulin Drugs by 70%, Cap Patient Costs at $3=
5 [ https://substack.com/redirect/115c6cff-bba4-4224-b9cf-e96489dbe239?j=3D=
eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Peter Loftus [ https://substack.com/redirect/8d2a1352-e006-4bc3-a3b4-3afad5=
4fa477?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=
 for The Wall Street Journal
The company also said that on May 1 it would reduce the list price of an un=
branded insulin it sells to $25 a vial from $82 a vial, the lowest level fo=
r any insulin that diabetes patients take around mealtimes, and less than L=
illy=E2=80=99s list price for a Humalog vial in 1999. And it plans to impro=
ve a program capping patients=E2=80=99 out-of-pocket costs at $35 a month [=
 https://substack.com/redirect/7f431336-512a-4950-8472-38108119ce9c?j=3DeyJ=
1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
It is hard to praise a company for lowering its prices on a necessary drug =
by 70%. Why? Because that means they=E2=80=99ve been price gouging for year=
s. That said, this move is life-changing for diabetes patients that are not=
 properly insured or are otherwise financially insecure. I personally could=
n=E2=80=99t imagine having to decide between dinner or medication, and for =
many people, that is the choice.
Again, we=E2=80=99re not going to praise Eli Lilly or any specific company =
here, but the hope is that a move like this drives down the price for simil=
ar medications on the market and generally makes predatory pricing practice=
s in pharma a bit more unacceptable.
Profits are important. They are the incentive for startups and big pharma c=
ompanies alike to take financial risk, innovate on moonshot drugs, and spen=
d years and years on expensive R&D and arduous approval processes. And Eli =
Lilly for sure has thoughtful rebuttals on how manufacturer rebates have go=
ne up, and market pricing dynamics, and yada yada, but the fact is that the=
y have priced-out life saving drugs from people that need it the most. We=
=E2=80=99re just glad these cuts are in place.
(2) SpaceX launches its 9th crewed mission as it heads to space station [ h=
ttps://substack.com/redirect/7df0bf45-77ab-4788-ac30-640af353acad?j=3DeyJ1I=
joiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Russel Lewis for NPR
Early Thursday morning, SpaceX launched its Crew Dragon capsule with four p=
eople aboard from the Kennedy Space Center. This is SpaceX=E2=80=99s ninth =
time sending astronauts into space over the last 3 years, and the seventh t=
ime they=E2=80=99ve done so in partnership with NASA.
The mission is meant to swap out the astronauts currently stationed at the =
International Space Station. Important work indeed, but nothing overly grou=
ndbreaking from a news perspective. But, at least in my mind, manned space =
missions are still a big deal. You can hear mission control getting all fir=
ed up in the video. It=E2=80=99s obviously still a big deal for them. Here=
=E2=80=99s to hoping for a future in which manned space travel is as common=
 as commercial airflight, and cheering upon takeoff/landing is just kind of=
 a weird kitschy thing we do.=20
(3) Stable Diffusion with Brain Activity [ https://substack.com/redirect/75=
f90efa-4c21-42fd-bb09-d6d25d0aed52?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaM=
ZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Yu Takagi and Shinji Nishimoto from Osaka University and NICT
Here, we propose a new method based on a diffusion model (DM) to reconstruc=
t images from human brain activity obtained via functional magnetic resonan=
ce imaging (fMRI). More specifically, we rely on a latent diffusion model (=
LDM) termed Stable Diffusion.
Soooo Stable Diffusion can read people=E2=80=99s minds now.=20
Researchers in Japan showed people images, scanned their brains in an fMRI,=
 and performed visual reconstruction of the images in Stable Diffusion. It =
worked surprisingly well =E2=80=94 those pictures above show the images peo=
ple were shown and the images Stable Diffusion reconstructed.=20
What=E2=80=99s maybe most incredible is that no training or fine-tuning of =
the deep models was needed to make it happen. The only training required wa=
s creating models that map fMRI signals to latent diffusion model component=
s, essentially giving Stable Diffusion something it could read.=20
The paper hasn=E2=80=99t been peer reviewed yet, but it=E2=80=99s a pretty =
stunning testament to the surprising out-of-the-box capabilities of these m=
odels.
Speaking of which=E2=80=A6 Zack Witten discovered that Bing Chat can play c=
hess. There are already chess-playing models, of course. Deep Blue beat Kas=
parov in 1997, and most top chess players today use the Stockfish Chess Eng=
ine. But Bing doesn=E2=80=99t use a Chess-specific model, it uses GPT-X. Th=
e fact that a general LLM can play Elo 1100-1200 chess with no specific tra=
ining is pretty unbelievable. It seems like we=E2=80=99re just scratching t=
he surface on what large language and latent diffusion models can do.=20
(4) Apartment Rents Fall as Crush of New Supply Hits Market [ https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/c68b872c-58e0-48e1-b282-9d0b7a957b4d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qif=
Q.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Will Parker [ https://substack.com/redirect/ce6e5475-1bfb-4693-9a24-f5274af=
2ffab?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] =
for The Wall Street Journal
Apartment rents fell in every major metropolitan area in the U.S. over the =
past six months through January, a trend that is poised to continue [ https=
://substack.com/redirect/be2f1098-8593-466e-a8de-7c7f18928d2e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiO=
XAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] as the biggest deli=
very of new apartments in nearly four decades is slated for this year.
Thank the Lord. Living in Manhattan for the past year has been disgustingly=
 expensive. Manhattan rent has always been expensive, but the last year rea=
lly felt like landlords were taking out some Covid-induced stress on prospe=
ctive renters. =E2=80=9CYes, remember those Covid deals you all signed and =
bragged about in early 2021? Well this is similar a deal, but monthly rent =
is going up 10% and those two free months are gone=E2=80=A6so net rent is e=
ffectively up 30%.=E2=80=9D
And there=E2=80=99s a reason NYC landlords and landlords all across major U=
=2ES. cities could pull this off. There s=
imply aren=E2=80=99t enough apartmen=
ts to comfortably accommodate all of the people moving to major cities. But=
 supply is starting to come on line to meet that demand, and that is loweri=
ng (or at least stalling increases) rents.
This is a reminder that building is good. More housing, all else equal, mea=
ns lower living costs. A win for YIMBYs!
(5) The Build-Nothing Country [ https://substack.com/redirect/a6bb6d2a-6a22=
-44ae-976c-6bc20a786d3f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbq=
Osa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Noah Smith [ https://substack.com/redirect/831f4cef-0146-4750-8445-f0b9f1cc=
d377?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] f=
or Noahpinion
Oops, we did it again. Another Noah Smith post. But, in fairness, this is a=
lready his most =E2=80=9Chearted" post on Substack (from what we can tell) =
and directly relevant to the post on building above.
The essay is, essentially, a well-evidenced rant on America=E2=80=99s inabi=
lity to build new things and the consequences of that inability. He takes o=
n housing, transit, green energy projects, and even semiconductors.
His conclusion is that America is willing to spend on big projects, but tha=
t spending doesn=E2=80=99t necessarily manifest as changes in the built wor=
ld. $5B earmarked for green energy projects in some bill, doesn=E2=80=99t n=
ecessarily mean we=E2=80=99re getting $5B worth of green energy projects. I=
t just means that $5,000,000,000 lives somewhere in some beaurocrat=E2=80=
=99s spreadsheet.
Why is this the case? According to Smith, this is the great American subsid=
y. America=E2=80=99s ability to spend, but inability to build is preserving=
 the built environment around us. Your house value stays high, your neighbo=
rhoods remain spacious, your streets inaccessible via transportation to rif=
raf, This seems like a no-cost subsidy but it=E2=80=99s not.=20
The costs are real, and Americans pay the costs. They pay them in the highe=
r tax bills that citizens pay to fund infrastructure. They pay them in the =
increased prices businesses have to charge to make up for higher land costs=
=2E They pay them in higher rents. They p=
ay those costs in more expensive ele=
ctricity and increased carbon emissions. They pay them in the lower wages t=
hat workers earn because their cities can=E2=80=99t build sufficient housin=
g near to the areas of greatest economic opportunity. They pay them in lowe=
r productivity because cities can=E2=80=99t grow big enough. They pay those=
 costs in lost wages and incomes from disinvestment, when companies decide =
that America=E2=80=99s obstacles to land development make it a bad country =
to build a factory in. And eventually they pay the cost of a weak country t=
hat doesn=E2=80=99t have the economic strength to stand up to rivals like C=
hina.
The stakes for building are high. And if America doesn=E2=80=99t step up to=
 the plate (we=E2=80=99re hopeful we will) some other country will.
Bonus: Not Boring Founders: Andrew Herr, Fount [ https://substack.com/redir=
ect/49a3fa40-55d9-42ac-90ef-25f6980be13d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_=
ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
We=E2=80=99re going to pump our own book for a second here, but in this cas=
e, we think it=E2=80=99s mutually beneficial. Packy and Andrew Herr, founde=
r and CEO of Fount, just dropped a new episode of Not Boring Founders. They=
 discuss Packy=E2=80=99s fitness and health journey. Packy went from a low-=
energy, kinda fat new dad to this [ https://substack.com/redirect/02b4720b-=
e6d7-4334-a476-ac9045dc19fd?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXe=
pKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] (asked for shirtless selfie, but did not get approval=
) largely thanks to working with the Fount team.
The name of the game is customization. Whatever plan works for Packy today,=
 may not work for Packy 6 months from now, and definitely won=E2=80=99t be =
optimized for you. Andrew=E2=80=99s company Fount [ https://substack.com/re=
direct/bfdb538a-9d58-48a3-8dad-426936bdb8a6?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7G=
nA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] takes customization to a whole new le=
vel: bloodwork, personalized supplement plans, nutrition and fitness plans,=
 1-on-1 training with former Navy Seals, etc. Today, Fount is expensive, bu=
t that=E2=80=99s just part of its larger plan [ https://substack.com/redire=
ct/723f9139-e6cc-4ab4-be10-5bb1df938e8f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Z=
lNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] to make customized health programs availa=
ble to anyone. It=E2=80=99s running a series of experiments on early custom=
ers in order to build data sets and software that make customized health pl=
ans accessible to everybody.
Health and wellness awareness is seemingly becoming mainstream. Huberman=E2=
=80=99s podcast is the #4 podcast in the entire world right now. And with t=
his rise, there=E2=80=99s been a rise of questionable health information an=
d influencers springing up. Andrew Herr is not one of them. Check out the c=
onvo for a real Fount of knowledge.=20
Did you enjoy reading this Weekly Dose of Optimism?
Yes [ https://substack.com/redirect/063ea9a0-e716-405f-aff2-0e84328a9105?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] | Meh [=
 https://substack.com/redirect/063ea9a0-e716-405f-aff2-0e84328a9105?j=3DeyJ=
